Halve, peel and chop the @Echalion shallot{2} into small ½cm pieces. Halve, peel and slice the @red onion{2} into thin half moon. Cut the @cherry tomatoes{2} in half. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Remove the @mint{2}(leaves removed and chopped) leaves from their stalks. Discard the stalks and chop the leaves. Slice each @halloumi{2} block into eight slices. Drain the @brown lentils{2%handfuls} in a #sieve{} or #colander{} and rinse under cold water.

Drizzle a good glug of @olive oil{} into a #saucepan{} on medium heat and add the red onion. Cook until really soft, ~{7%minutes}. Add the @balsamic vinegar{2}, pop a lid on and turn the heat down to low. Cook until nicely caramelised, stirring occasionally, ~{8-10%minutes}. Transfer to a #bowl{} and set aside. Wipe out the pan.

Heat a drizzle of oil in another #frying pan{} on medium heat, add the shallot. Cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Add the tomatoes, a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Cook for ~{5%minutes} more. Add the garlic and stir. Cook for another ~{1%minute}. Next add the lentils along with another pinch of salt and black pepper. Stir together. Warm through for ~{3%minutes}. Add the @baby spinach{1}(washed and ready) pop a lid on and leave to the side (off the heat) to wilt the spinach.

While the spinach wilts, put the (now empty) pan you used for the onions on medium heat and add a drizzle of oil. Once the oil is hot, lay in the halloumi slices. Cook for ~{3%minutes} on each side until golden. Remove the pan from the heat.

Add half the mint to the lentil mixture and stir together (if the spinach hasn't wilted completely, that's fine!).

Serve the lentil mixture in bowls with the halloumi slices on top. Spoon over the caramelised red onion and finish with the remaining mint and @pumpkin seeds{30%g}. Enjoy!